            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Technical Analysis (TA) - TA utilizes daily stock charts in order to determine entries, areas to reduce, and exists for your positions.  While the breadth of information is quite large, I will cover a few of the key concepts so you can know what I am talking about.<span>

            <ol class="terms-list">
                <li class="text-left font-size-1 mb-2">
                  <span> <strong>Price Bar -</strong>  </span> <span>a price bar can be on any time frame, but I generally look at it on a daily level.  A price bar consists of a price level at the open of the market, the close of the market, as well as a high and low level for the day.  </span>
                </li>
                <%= image_tag "ohlc.png", alt: "Price bar", class: 'picture-2' %>

                <li class="text-left font-size-1 mb-2">
                  <p> <strong>Stock Base -</strong>  </p> <p>A stock base consists of an amalgamation of price bars.  A base is a controlled trading range where price either remains flat ( a flat base) contracts (Cup and Handle), or wedges down ( often called a bull flag).  The concept of a base is simple - in each case a stock has run up its price.  Eventually the excitement cools down and the price starts to slow down and consolidate.   </p>

                  <p> <strong>A flat base -</strong>  Here is a flat base on FNKO around a year ago using weekly bars. This pattern has easily defined highs and lows.  The length of these depends on a lot, and is one of the questions I am looking at in my modeling.  For now, we assume that they last at least 4 weeks or more.</p>
                  <%= image_tag "flat-base.png", alt: "Flat Base", class: 'picture-2' %>

                  <p> <strong>Cup and Handle -</strong>  Fancy name for a stock that is seeing a base with decreasing volatility.  The range of the price bars start to decrease in amplitude.  Basically people are becoming less interested in it so people aren’t trading it as frequently.  Bill O’Neil coined this term. This one was Qualcom during the 1999 dot come bubble, and it ran up big time after this set up. </p>
                  <%= image_tag "cah.png", alt: "Flat Base", class: 'picture-2' %>

                  <p> <strong>Bull Flag -</strong>  Another name for a price consolidation - the price bars move downward as weaker buyers sell their holdings.  The reason it is called a bull flag is because it is a continuation pattern within a bull market.  Obviously the reverse can (and does) occur in bear markets. This one was BMEA which broke out on 6/7/2022 during the bear market rally of the summer.    </p>
                  <%= image_tag "bull-flag.png", alt: "Bull Flag", class: 'picture-2' %>

                  <p>There are many more considerations than what I listed here, but this should be sufficient to understand the context on my blog.  Remember patterns are not anywhere close to 100%, and it takes time to spot them and act on them correctly.  Don’t expect this to be a magic bullet. </p>
                </li>

              </ol>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1">
            <p class="font-size-1 mb-1"> <strong>Breakouts </strong>  </p>
            <p class="font-size-1 mb-2">  Pivotal points are regions of price where the price must move in order to purchase it.  When price moves through this region, it is called a breakout.  The volume (number of shares) must be very high in order to consider it a strong breakout.  I purchase breakouts in bull markets, but not in bear markets.<p>

            <p>In this case, the pivotal region was a line connecting the highs of the price bars from the past few weeks. This one was Cisco from fall of 2022.  It ran up a little after this.</p>
            <%= image_tag "breakout.png", alt: "Bull Flag", class: 'picture-2' %>

            <p>Questions concerning how much volume is needed for the day in order to buy a breakout is something that my market model will answer in due time.  I will post that data as I find candidates for purchase</p>


            </li>

            </li>

             <li class="text-left font-size-1"><p class="font-size-1 mb-3"><strong>Fundmentals</strong> - The fundamentals of a company play an important role is determining how long the stock will run for.  If a stock is running on pure momentum based on speculation, it is likely the price will crash as fast as it rose ( or faster).   What I look for with my selections is (generally) growing sales, gross margins, net income, net margins, and widening operating leverage.  We don’t necessarily need all.  I also like a new product or service combined with somewhat low following.   <span>

             <p>Specifically what I look for is accelerating quarterly year over year rates of change for sales, margins and earnings over the past 4 quarters.  My stock model will quantitatively determine these rates of changes for previous winners at the start of their runs, and when their runs ended.  </p>


             </li>




            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><p class="font-size-1 mb-3"><strong>Macroeconomic big picture</strong> -   <span>

             <p>It is possible to trade stocks without context of the macroeconomic environment.  However getting the long term macro correct will avoid (in general) being on the wrong side of trades.  I’ll confess I outsource this task to a buddy of mine who manages his own family office.  I am familiar with the system he employs, and will only discuss it at a very high level here.  Essentially one can determine the likely positioning of professional money based upon the rates of change of growth an inflation.  This was originally presented as Ray Dalios work, but has been adopted elsewhere.  Essentially one is to be weary of being positioned heavily in equity markets as growth is slowing an inflation is (a) slowing or (b) accelerating.   </p>

             <p>The federal reserve is another important consideration when considering long-term exposure to markets.  In particular the fed has been known to move markets during ( recently before) the setting of the short term fed funds target.  Higher rates means tighter liquidity which generally poses a challenge for stock performance.  More recently, quantitative easing ( QE) must be considered as well.  Quantitative easing is the process of adding liquidity to the financial system as the federal reserve purchases fixed income instruments such as treasury debt and Mortgage backed securities form member banks.  Watching the rate of change of money on the federal reserves balance sheet generally shows how much money will go into/out of the system whereby one can make an approximation for stock performance.  I have not been able to model it as of yet. </p>


             </li>



            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> <strong>Indicators -</strong>  I use a few other indicators including the McClellan Summation Index, and tick data during the day.  The McClellan Summation Index will show the general participation of stocks.  If it is going up this simply means more stocks are moving up and if its down, this means more stocks are moving down. (thanks detective)  Tick data shows the buying and selling pressure during moves.  Finally I record breadth data by hand every day - this includes (a) number of advancing stocks/ declining stocks, (b) net net new highs ( highs minus lows), and (c) advancing volume and declining volume for the NYSE and NASDAQ listings.<span></li>

            <span>

