            <h2 class="text-left section-header mb-4">Trading Rules</h2>
                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">Anyone wishing to trade using a method like this must employ their own set of rules.   I follow these without exceptions.

                </p>

           <ol class="terms-list">
            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"><strong>Stop Losses -</strong></span>
            <span class="font-size-1">Prior to entering a trade, determine a price level where you will exit the trade if you are wrong.  These levels can vary from very tight (1% to 2%) all the way up to 7% or so.  My typical stop loss is 5% or around 1-1.5% of my total equity.  This allows two things (1) to get out when you are wrong and preserve capital and (2) stay in the trade when a shakeout occurs.  There is a tradeoff between tight stops and being shaken out.  You will have to figure this out on your own, but in general utilize the 14-period average true range as a maximum stop loss distance.   If my stop is hit, I am out.  There is no exception to this rule.  </span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"><strong>Breakouts -</strong></span>
            <span class="font-size-1">Only purchase a stock if it is moving out of a price consolidation during a bull market.  This pivot area is usually new highs, and should be accompanied by volume when viewed on the weekly chart. (I.E the volume might come in a few days after a breakout).  Do not chase a stock that has already broken out for more than a day and is more than 5% above its pivot region.  Reduce some 3-5 days after a breakout.  In a bull market reduce a smaller amount such as 20% or 30%, whereas in a bear market its smarter to reduce a larger %.    <span></li>


            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">If a momentum stock without large earnings moves up very quickly, sell some of the position ( 20% to 30%) and lock in profit.  When the stock has moved up to 3 times your total risk, raise the stop loss to break even.  When a stock has moved up past your average profit, move the stop loss to this level.  Never let a profitable position turn into a loss.   <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> If the stock in question is a high pedigree name and has a strong earnings profile, a new product, forward thinking management and it is up 20% in under 3 weeks from a large base, the stock must be held for 8 weeks at a minimum.  This rule is directly from Bill O’Niel’s book, ‘How to Make Money in Stocks”<span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> To keep things simple, I use a trailing stop of the 10 simple moving average or the 20 simple moving average to reduce my positions on the bullish ( or bearish) side.   <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> If twitter or friends start talking about a stock, its time to start considering when to exit.  Don't follow the crowd unless you want to lose money like the crowd.    <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Don’t hold through an earnings report unless you have a huge profit in a stock.
             Don't initiate a position before earnings unless you are a degenerate gambler. <span></li>


            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Hold onto winners, and sell losers quickly.  <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">I don't do options often, if ever.  <span></li>



